Germany : a costly fiscal fetish
FRANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is facing fierce attacks in Germany, a country that has long prided itself on defending the principle of central bank independence.
Indeed, it was Germany that insisted this principle be included in the criteria outlined by the Maastricht Treaty, which set the conditions for membership in the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), the decision to grant independence to their central bank in order to join the eurozone implied a political regime change.
Thus, the independence of the Bank of France, during the ratification referendum of the Maastricht Treaty in 1992, was one of the strongest arguments of the campaign against joining the euro.
In today's Germany, it has become commonplace, one might say, to exert pressure on the central bank.
For several months, even the Finance Minister, Wolfgang Schaüble, has regularly commented on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Schaüble's interventions target the very core of what constitutes the central bank's independence.
Although he does not seek to redefine the objective of monetary policy (this "price stability" in the former jargon of the Bundesbank), he nonetheless provides his advice on the tools the ECB should use and how it should handle them to achieve such an aim.
We have seen precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then German Finance Minister, gave his advice to the first president of the ECB, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's aim was, in the end, to create a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with his typical Dutch brevity, replied that it was nothing unusual for a politician to express his opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, this was absolutely unheard of). "However – he added – it would be entirely abnormal to take account of [his] suggestions."

The respect for monetary policy independence has long been a central element of the German "Stabilitätkultur" («culture of stability»).
The founding act of the Bundesbank's reputation for strict independence was its refusal to yield to Chancellor Konrad Adenauer's urgings, who wanted it to contain the rise in interest rates in 1956.
At that time, France saw things differently.
Charles de Gaulle was about to create the Fifth Republic, with a Banque de France that reported to the Minister of Finance.
But it was another time.
Following various crises that shook the Economic and Monetary Union, monetary policy has increasingly tended to replace fiscal policy.
Has the old dogma become obsolete?
The Europe remains very vulnerable; the median inhabitant of the ERM has already lost ten years, and, what is even more alarming, we are close to a critical situation.
However, the United States are doing better.
Despite a difficult political stalemate to manage, they have managed to tackle the macroeconomic issue (the weakness of aggregate demand) they were facing by launching expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The United States have also better managed their banking problems, which, at the outset, were far more severe than in Europe.
(There is obviously a strong interaction between the measures that can be taken in both areas.
The more an economy is robust, the more its banks are profitable and the more they are able to fulfill their function: financing the economy.)
But the independence of the ECB is less threatened by the good advice of a finance minister than by the lack of public support.
Indeed, the famous autonomy of the Bundesbank relied less on its legal status than on the indelible support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
Exactly the opposite is true of the ECB.
Voices are being heard, notably in Germany, calling for it to be subjected to more pressure.
But the greatest threat to the ECB's autonomy lies in the unbearable burden that weighs on its shoulders.
The less fiscal policy is called upon to stabilize production, the more central banks are de facto forced to take on this objective (unless, of course, they are designed to let nature take its course, allowing the economy to get stuck in stagnation, or worse).
The political result of this chain of events is a very clear regression toward nationalism, both from the right and the left, in all countries of the ERM, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical corollary of the policies pursued.
It is endogenous.
And there too, Germany leads the dance, driven by its obsession with the schwarze Null, budget balance, against all winds and tides.
In Germany, deficits are viewed unfavourably, not only from an arithmetic but also a moral standpoint, even though this defies economic common sense and resembles clientelism.
At the end of the 19th century, the main German specialists in public finance, including Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, formulated a « golden rule » according to which current expenditures should be financed, on average, by current revenues.
Public spending, and the resources it requires, are justified by their utility.
This amounts to saying that investments aimed at improving productivity – capital expenditures – can be financed with debt, whose service is ensured by the growth of incomes and the base of associated revenues.
This classical approach has been institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenditures and investment expenditures, which is always practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and in Austria).
This is crucial, because in Germany, about 50% of public sector investment expenditures are managed at this level (a proportion that has been declining, since the municipal share was two-thirds at the beginning of the 1990s).
These expenditures are consistent with supporting the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (Mittelstand).
However, compared to the beginning of the 1990s and at constant prices, investment expenditures have decreased by about 15%.
More than a decade has passed, and they have been insufficient to maintain the capital stock.
If this is not how the future is prepared, this is how productivity and prosperity are undermined.
In short, the schwarze Null goes against the goal it seeks to achieve.
Outdated infrastructure (though not as much as in the United States) has become a real problem for Germany.
Furthermore, the fiscal frugality of German leaders spills over German borders, and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which does not have exchange rates to accommodate national particularities.
Of course, the European monetary union is imperfect.
But to make the only institution ready to « do what is necessary » to bring the ERM back on track into a scapegoat is a very bad idea.
For states to use, where it exists, the budgetary space they have to relieve pressure on the ECB would be a much better strategy.
Germany, without a doubt, enjoys a certain degree of maneuvering room in this regard.
